<P>ACCOMMODATION, A POETICAL EPISTLE, <HI>&amp;c.</HI></P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="title page">
<PB REF="2">
<P>ACCOMMODATION, A POETICAL EPISTLE TO JOHN ASHBY, <ABBR>E&s;q</ABBR></P>
<P>BY <HI>ROWLEY THOMAS.</HI></P>
<Q>QUI MORES HOMINUM MULTORUM VIDIT.&mdash;<BIBL>HOR.</BIBL></Q>
<P><HI>SHREWSBURY:</HI> Printed by J. EDDOWES, for the AUTHOR. MDCCLXXV.</P>
</DIV1>
</FRONT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="text">
<PB N="1" REF="3">
<HEAD><HI>ACCOMMODATION,</HI> &amp;c.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L><HI>CONDESCENSION</HI> in the mu&s;e</L>
<L><HI>Severe&s;t critics</HI> will excu&s;e;</L>
<L><HI>Conde&s;cen&s;ion</HI> in the man</L>
<L>Is the <HI>&s;kilful, winning,</HI> plan:</L>
<L>By conde&s;cen&s;ion, here, I mean</L>
<L><HI>Accommodation in the &s;cene</HI></L>
<L><HI>Of life.&mdash;</HI>Will <HI>A---y</HI> conde&s;cend</L>
<L>To view the trifler in the friend;</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB N="2" REF="4">
<L>That friend who ever has, and will</L>
<L>Protect his character from ill;</L>
<L>Give up life,&mdash;all <HI>fancy's power,</HI></L>
<L>To cheer his every anxious hour?</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Then &s;urely <HI>A---y</HI> can't refu&s;e</L>
<L>The <HI>whim&s;eys</HI> of a <HI>flighty mu&s;e.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>A <HI>bland, goodnatur'd, mu&s;e</HI> that mu&s;t</L>
<L>Protect the good,&mdash;the great,&mdash;the ju&s;t;</L>
<L>Protect the wi&s;e,&mdash;protect the brave,&mdash;</L>
<L>All,&mdash;All,&mdash;but <HI>coward, fool,</HI> and <HI>knave:</HI></L>
<L>And cowards, fools, and knaves &s;hall be</L>
<L>The objects of <HI>her charity.</HI></L>
<L>Then <HI>A---y</HI> &s;urely will excu&s;e</L>
<L>An <HI>idle, truant, laughing mu&s;e;</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB N="3" REF="5">
<L>A mu&s;e that ever will incline</L>
<L>To favour <HI>A---y</HI> with a line;&mdash;</L>
<L>&mdash;His <HI>gentlene&s;s</HI> can ne'er refu&s;e</L>
<L><HI>The fondly,&mdash;overweening mu&s;e;</HI></L>
<L>That oft <HI>in per&s;on</HI> will attend him,</L>
<L>And <HI>coun&s;el quaint</HI> will freely lend him:</L>
<L>Then <HI>A---y</HI> never can refu&s;e</L>
<L>The <HI>gambols</HI> of this <HI>frolic</HI> mu&s;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>How!&mdash;&s;ays, <HI>Sir critic;&mdash;</HI>not to brand</L>
<L>With infamy the murdering hand;</L>
<L>And every character that can</L>
<L>Sink to the <HI>brute</HI> from <HI>rea&s;oning man!</HI></L>
<L><HI>&mdash;Avaunt ra&s;h critici&s;m!&mdash;</HI>Learn ye!</L>
<L><HI>He &s;erv'd his time to vile attorney;</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB N="4" REF="6">
<L>And <HI>vile attorneys</HI> ne'er can be</L>
<L>Fit &s;ubjects for <HI>a la&s;h from thee:</HI></L>
<L><HI>&mdash;We then</HI> &s;hould <HI>too much</HI> conde&s;cend.&mdash;</L>
<L>What!&mdash;Give our &s;atire for no end!</L>
<L>No!&mdash;Let him canter o'er the hill</L>
<L>Of <HI>wild Parna&s;&s;us with his quill;</HI></L>
<L>And &s;tumble on without a note</L>
<L>From us, who <HI>think</HI> and <HI>write by</HI> rote.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>The con&s;cious mu&s;e, in native charms,</L>
<L>Laughs,&mdash;'till &s;he bur&s;ts,&mdash;at &s;uch alarms;</L>
<L><HI>Dares</HI> every critic to defiance,</L>
<L>&mdash;She never wi&s;hes <HI>&s;uch alliance;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Dares</HI> every critic with a frown,&mdash;</L>
<L>To laud her,<HI>&mdash;up;</HI> to bla&s;t her,<HI>&mdash;down.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB N="5" REF="7">
<L>With indignation now &s;he burns,</L>
<L>And gladly to that friend returns;&mdash;</L>
<L>Who gave her, with a <HI>gentle hand,</HI></L>
<L>And <HI>feeling heart,</HI> each &s;weet command:&mdash;</L>
<L>What to <HI>embrace,&mdash;</HI>and what to <HI>fly</HI></L>
<L><HI>During her term of &s;lavery.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Kind,&mdash;gentle &s;pirit!&mdash;yet e'en he</L>
<L>Can &s;carce e&s;cape &s;everity;</L>
<L>Who&s;e <HI>noble mind,&mdash;</HI>and <HI>&s;welling heart,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Their virtues</HI> cheerfully impart</L>
<L><HI>TO MAN AT LARGE:&mdash;</HI>without a dream</L>
<L>Of <HI>&s;elf</HI>'s attractive,&mdash;darling theme;</L>
<L>That <HI>lu&s;cious,&mdash;dear,&mdash;engaging thing,</HI></L>
<L>Which &s;ways alike <HI>the clown,&mdash;the king;&mdash;</HI></L>
<L><PB N="6" REF="8">
At every place,&mdash;at every hour,&mdash;</L>
<L>Gives <HI>&s;trange exemplars</HI> of it's power.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>The <HI>cheerful reader</HI> too 'll excu&s;e</L>
<L>The <HI>queer digre&s;&s;ions</HI> of the mu&s;e;</L>
<L>And give her credit for awhile</L>
<L>For every laugh,&mdash;for every &s;mile;&mdash;</L>
<L>Which &s;he engages to exert,&mdash;</L>
<L>Neither too timorous,&mdash;nor pert;</L>
<L>As opportunity permits,&mdash;</L>
<L>And &s;he can &s;trike &s;ome lucky hits.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>Her fir&s;t e&s;&s;ay;&mdash;and all her own.</HI></L>
<L><HI>&mdash;Sir critic,</HI> fy!&mdash;&s;uppre&s;s that frown!&mdash;</L>
<L><PB N="7" REF="9">
&mdash;Solicits favor, from&mdash;</L>
<L><HI>&mdash;A FRIEND:&mdash;</HI></L>
<L>And, if &s;he meet with his applau&s;e,</L>
<L>Will lengthen out her <HI>little cau&s;e:&mdash;</HI></L>
<L><HI>&mdash;By daring,</HI> in &s;ome future plan,</L>
<L><NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">Analy&s;is <HI>of the human character;&mdash;begun by the author of this little performance;&mdash;&s;howing</HI> POPE's E&s;&s;ay on man <HI>unintelligible,</HI> as a fini&s;hed,&mdash;philo&s;ophical, piece; <HI>but</HI> largely &s;ub&s;cribing <HI>to the</HI> inimitable beauties of it, <HI>as a</HI> merely poetical one.</NOTE> <HI>To analyze that creature man;</HI></L>
<L>Whether in poetry, or pro&s;e,</L>
<L>Is in&s;ignificant to tho&s;e,</L>
<L><HI>Who think,&mdash;who act,&mdash;</HI>from <HI>nature's &s;chool,</HI></L>
<L>And never idly play the fool:&mdash;</L>
<L>&mdash;As whilom <HI>THOMAS</HI> often did,</L>
<L>Without his ever being chid;&mdash;</L>
<L>Except by &s;uch,&mdash;as never knew,</L>
<L><HI>Skilful</HI> to give the <HI>fine&s;pun clew</HI></L>
<L><PB N="8" REF="10">
To mild conver&s;ion's calm retreat;&mdash;</L>
<L>&mdash;Where all the <HI>mu&s;es,&mdash;graces</HI> meet;&mdash;</L>
<L>And every <HI>gho&s;t,&mdash;</HI>and every <HI>&s;hade,</HI></L>
<L>Of <HI>GODLIKE MAN,&mdash;</HI>that <HI>GOD</HI> has made:</L>
<L>Mid&s;t &s;cenes of <HI>wilde&s;t di&s;&s;ipation</HI> lo&s;t;&mdash;</L>
<L>His <HI>&s;en&s;ibility too often cro&s;t;&mdash;</HI></L>
<L>Thro' the <HI>kindlie&s;t warmth of blood,</HI></L>
<L>De&s;erting every <HI>&s;ocial good:</HI></L>
<L>This, and that, perver&s;e vexation</L>
<L>Springing all from circulation</L>
<L>Of <HI>boiling blood,&mdash;</HI>thro' every vein</L>
<L>Quick-trembling to it's &s;ource again,&mdash;</L>
<L><HI>The heart;&mdash;</HI>whence every rapture flows</L>
<L>For every good, which it be&s;tows</L>
<L>On kindred man:&mdash;without a thought</L>
<L>Of being a&s;k'd for,&mdash;being &s;ought.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB N="9" REF="11">
<L><HI>Spite of</HI> all the rage of fa&s;hion,&mdash;</L>
<L><HI>Spite of</HI> every wayward pa&s;&s;ion,&mdash;</L>
<L><HI>Spite of nature's oppo&s;ition;&mdash;</HI></L>
<L>He means to make a &s;trange tran&s;ition</L>
<L>From <HI>bad</HI> to <HI>good;&mdash;offhand</HI> reclaim</L>
<L>Each <HI>immoral,</HI> youthful aim;</L>
<L>And &s;tranger &s;till!&mdash;for <HI>quirking &s;eats</HI></L>
<L>Barter the <HI>mu&s;e's green retreats.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Hold!&mdash;cries, <HI>dame prudence;&mdash;</HI>hold your hand</L>
<L>And li&s;ten to this &s;age command.&mdash;</L>
<L><HI>Beware, young man!&mdash;</HI>with caution rove</L>
<L>O'er <HI>legal bank,&mdash;</HI>thro' <HI>quibbling grove;&mdash;</HI></L>
<L>Let <HI>law,</HI> and <HI>rea&s;on,&mdash;PRUDENCE</HI> join;&mdash;</L>
<L><HI>Then, then!</HI> you &s;trike a good de&s;ign.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB N="10" REF="12">
<L>* * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * </L>
<L>* * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * </L>
<L><HI>Cur&s;e on</HI> your tame,&mdash;your frigid notions</L>
<L>And all &s;uch <HI>quack,&mdash;cathartic potions.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>The <HI>GOD OF NATURE</HI> gave us pa&s;&s;ions,&mdash;</L>
<L>To <HI>grace us with</HI> on all occa&s;ions;</L>
<L>And gave us <HI>rea&s;on</HI> to control</L>
<L>The <HI>frantic &s;allies</HI> of the &s;oul.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>Pa&s;t follies!&mdash;Nature</HI> ought to bear,</L>
<L>And think <HI>him highly worth</HI> her care.</L>
<L>* * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * </L>
<L>* * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * </L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB N="11" REF="13">
<L>With all his faults,&mdash;and all his folly,</L>
<L>He's freed at length from <HI>MELANCHOLY;</HI></L>
<L>And her attendant,<HI>&mdash;APATHY.&mdash;</HI></L>
<L>&mdash;Dull,<HI>&mdash;cynic apathy!&mdash;</HI>who&s;e boa&s;t,</L>
<L>And blunted prai&s;e is always lo&s;t,&mdash;</L>
<L>By <HI>&s;eldom thinking,&mdash;never acting;&mdash;</HI></L>
<L>And yet it ever <HI>&s;eems tran&s;acting.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>A mere machine,&mdash;</HI>we u&s;e at will,</L>
<L>And keep it <HI>going on,&mdash;or &s;till,</HI></L>
<L><HI>As fancy leads:&mdash;</HI>a <HI>moping jade;&mdash;</HI></L>
<L><HI>A piece of clockwork,&mdash;</HI>only made</L>
<L>For <HI>keene&s;t cuts</HI> of <HI>comic wit,&mdash;</HI></L>
<L>Ju&s;t when <HI>my lady</HI>'s in the fit</L>
<L>To flouri&s;h o'er <HI>wild nature</HI>'s page,</L>
<L>And <HI>&s;tamp the wretch</HI> of every age.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB N="12" REF="14" MS="y">
<L>The cruel critics &s;till abu&s;e</L>
<L>The <HI>whim&s;ical,&mdash;meandrous mu&s;e;&mdash;</HI></L>
<L>Without one &s;ocial feeling dare</L>
<L>To bla&s;t <HI>my fir&s;t,&mdash;my only care;</HI></L>
<L>And dully critici&s;ing &s;ay;&mdash;</L>
<L>The pillars, when they artle&s;s lay,</L>
<L>The &s;uper&s;tructure mu&s;t betray:&mdash;</L>
<L>Quickly the <HI>ca&s;tle</HI>'s undermin'd</L>
<L>And by a <HI>trifling gale of wind.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>So fare the laurel and the bays</L>
<L>Of &s;uch a rhyme&s;ter's <HI>jingling lays;&mdash;</HI></L>
<L>&mdash;His <HI>canting,&mdash;puling,&mdash;lukewarm,&mdash;</HI></L>
<L>The <HI>brawling brats</HI> of <HI>colde&s;t climes,&mdash;</HI></L>
<L>The <HI>laurel</HI> claim and <HI>blooming bays,</HI></L>
<L>Without the lea&s;t pretence to prai&s;e:&mdash;</L>
<L><PB N="13" REF="15">
&mdash;Let gentle&s;t breezes gently come,</L>
<L>They &s;hake his <HI>high-a&s;piring plume,&mdash;</HI></L>
<L>Which trembling drops,&mdash;without a tear</L>
<L>From us who give him,<HI>&mdash;every fear.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>And now, <HI>AERIAL GENIUS!&mdash;</HI>now</L>
<L>Stoop to my mu&s;e,&mdash;&s;he'll teach you, how</L>
<L><HI>To &s;weep the &s;kilful,&mdash;winning bow.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Bend <HI>genius,&mdash;</HI>bend!&mdash;accept this <HI>new,&mdash;</HI></L>
<L><HI>This grand,&mdash;accommodating clew;</HI></L>
<L>&mdash;Nobly defend the mu&s;e's claim</L>
<L>A <HI>mirthful mu&s;e</HI>'s hone&s;t aim.&mdash;</L>
<L><PB N="14" REF="16">
<HI>&mdash;And when dull apathi&s;ts perceive</HI></L>
<L>That you the <HI>my&s;tic mu&s;e</HI> can believe;&mdash;</L>
<L>They'll <HI>crawl it on,&mdash;in faith with you,</HI></L>
<L>And own them&s;elves <HI>high-honoured</HI> too.&mdash;</L>
<L>&mdash;Let but the lower ranks comply,&mdash;</L>
<L>You'll have the <HI>mu&s;e's leave</HI> to fly,&mdash;</L>
<L>And <HI>&s;oar it to</HI> your native &s;ky.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>Fir&s;t</HI> let the <HI>towering genius</HI> dare</L>
<L>To make <HI>high worth</HI> his <HI>con&s;tant care;&mdash;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Next</HI> let the towering genius bend</L>
<L>To make each <HI>hone&s;t heart,&mdash;his friend.</HI></L>
<L>And never think it worth his part</L>
<L>To court <HI>the head without the heart:&mdash;</HI></L>
<L><PB N="15" REF="17">
<HI>&mdash;We grant,&mdash;</HI>that where they kindly meet,</L>
<L><HI>The union</HI> forms <HI>an higher treat:&mdash;</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>But a good heart,&mdash;the deity will own,&mdash;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Far,&mdash;far excels,&mdash;the merely laurel'd crown.</HI></L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
